{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/mastering-paper/drawing-water/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"frontmatter":{"title":"Mastering Paper for iOS: drawing water and waves","date":"2013-09-29T00:00:00.000Z","date_pretty":"September 29th, 2013","date_from_now":"7 years ago","last_modified_at":"2019-09-13T12:32:18.000Z","last_modified_at_from_now":"10 months ago","path":"/mastering-paper/drawing-water/","author":null,"excerpt":"Methods for drawing water and waves using the iPad app Paper for iOS.","tags":["Paper for iOS","tutorial","Apple"],"image":{"childImageSharp":{"fluid":{"aspectRatio":2.5700934579439254,"src":"/static/efc41c9c85c3ef2f222547e4e9e2f6d5/fc20c/paper-53-water-guide-feature.jpg","srcSet":"/static/efc41c9c85c3ef2f222547e4e9e2f6d5/6e883/paper-53-water-guide-feature.jpg 275w,\n/static/efc41c9c85c3ef2f222547e4e9e2f6d5/a09ef/paper-53-water-guide-feature.jpg 550w,\n/static/efc41c9c85c3ef2f222547e4e9e2f6d5/fc20c/paper-53-water-guide-feature.jpg 1100w,\n/static/efc41c9c85c3ef2f222547e4e9e2f6d5/356ef/paper-53-water-guide-feature.jpg 1280w","sizes":"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px"},"fixed":{"src":"/static/efc41c9c85c3ef2f222547e4e9e2f6d5/fc20c/paper-53-water-guide-feature.jpg","height":430,"width":1100}}},"toc":true,"comments":true,"comments_locked":true,"hide_meta":null},"id":"7aa89abe-ef78-5fcb-9579-f12d05605f78","html":"<p>Hopefully parts 2 and 3 of my <a href=\"/mastering-paper/\">Mastering Paper by FiftyThree Guide</a> demonstrated just how easy drawing trees and skies on an iPad can be. Building on the techniques in those tutorials, I’m going to walk you through my process for drawing water and waves — perfect for beach and coastline illustrations! If you enjoyed how I draw clouds, the following should be familiar territory since I use similar techniques.</p>\n<h2 id=\"mixing-the-water\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#mixing-the-water\" aria-label=\"mixing the water permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Mixing the water</h2>\n<p>When choosing a color for the water, I like to mix it dull and gray by knocking the saturation down<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup>. I find this helps arrive at a better base color and contrasts nicely against a bright blue sky. But don’t let this mix limit your creative vision, make it any color you want.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 61.81818181818181%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of blue-gray water color mix\"\n        title=\"screenshot of blue-gray water color mix\"\n        data-src=\"/static/5573b1a07a91d9aa8f974688d6fdf3ac/062c0/paper-53-water-color-mix.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/5573b1a07a91d9aa8f974688d6fdf3ac/16841/paper-53-water-color-mix.jpg 275w,\n/static/5573b1a07a91d9aa8f974688d6fdf3ac/50c97/paper-53-water-color-mix.jpg 550w,\n/static/5573b1a07a91d9aa8f974688d6fdf3ac/062c0/paper-53-water-color-mix.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<div class=\"custom-block notice\"><div class=\"custom-block-heading\">ProTip: start light</div><div class=\"custom-block-body\"><p>Don’t make the mix too dark. You’ll achieve better results by applying multiple lighter coats instead of going at it with one. Mix the desired color<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> you’d like to end up with and then lower the saturation and luminosity about 25% each.</p></div></div>\n<p>Much like drawing skies, you can choose to mark a horizon line in pencil to act as a guide — or go commando if you’re confident in your watercolor skills. If you decide to draw the horizon, remember to keep it light so it doesn’t bleed through the watercolor we’ll be applying next.</p>\n<div class=\"custom-block notice\"><div class=\"custom-block-heading\">ProTip: smart cover ruler</div><div class=\"custom-block-body\"><p>An iPad smart cover placed on the screen can be used as a straight edge for drawing lines if you don’t have a ruler handy.</p><p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 49.81818181818182%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"using an iPad smart cover as a ruler\"\n        title=\"using an iPad smart cover as a ruler\"\n        data-src=\"/static/309607dde95e094f6056145020a334d9/062c0/paper-53-smart-cover-rule.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/309607dde95e094f6056145020a334d9/16841/paper-53-smart-cover-rule.jpg 275w,\n/static/309607dde95e094f6056145020a334d9/50c97/paper-53-smart-cover-rule.jpg 550w,\n/static/309607dde95e094f6056145020a334d9/062c0/paper-53-smart-cover-rule.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p></div></div>\n<h3 id=\"base-coat-for-the-water\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#base-coat-for-the-water\" aria-label=\"base coat for the water permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Base coat for the water</h3>\n<p>With our blue-gray mixed and ready, select the watercolor brush and paint a slow and even stroke to make up this first layer of water. Just like painting skies, you’re trying for an even application of watercolor without lifting your stylus or finger off the iPad’s screen. Work your stroke from top to bottom, left to right, overlapping the previously painted portion slightly. A slow stroke with a slight zig zag to it will aid in painting an even and homogeneous tone quickly.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.54545454545455%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of water with a layer base coat\"\n        title=\"screenshot of water with a layer base coat\"\n        data-src=\"/static/17934bbbd0cdb99a4d25960440058709/062c0/paper-53-water-base-coat.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/17934bbbd0cdb99a4d25960440058709/16841/paper-53-water-base-coat.jpg 275w,\n/static/17934bbbd0cdb99a4d25960440058709/50c97/paper-53-water-base-coat.jpg 550w,\n/static/17934bbbd0cdb99a4d25960440058709/062c0/paper-53-water-base-coat.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Start with 2–3 even coats filling in the water with as smooth a tone as you can. Depending on how many wave troughs there will be, you may have to gradually fade the tone as you move down. The water I’m painting in this example is fairly flat, so keeping the tone smooth throughout is the goal here.</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 43.27272727272728%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"screenshot faded blue water with two coats\" title=\"screenshot faded blue water with two coats\" data-src=\"/static/685299659043ec654f6db09882ecb9cb/062c0/paper-53-water-fade-reference.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/685299659043ec654f6db09882ecb9cb/16841/paper-53-water-fade-reference.jpg 275w,\n/static/685299659043ec654f6db09882ecb9cb/50c97/paper-53-water-fade-reference.jpg 550w,\n/static/685299659043ec654f6db09882ecb9cb/062c0/paper-53-water-fade-reference.jpg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p>In the photo reference to the right you&apos;ll notice the water is darkest at the horizon and gradually fades down &#x2014; that&apos;s the effect you&apos;re looking to replicate by increasing the speed of your stroke as you approach the bottom.</p></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<div class=\"custom-block notice\"><div class=\"custom-block-heading\">ProTip: dark to light</div><div class=\"custom-block-body\"><p>Applying multiple coats adjacent to the horizon line and lightening as you work down will add dimension to the painting. Fading into the paper will also give you more flexibility later if you decide to add a beach or coastline.</p></div></div>\n<h3 id=\"adding-wave-chop\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#adding-wave-chop\" aria-label=\"adding wave chop permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Adding wave chop</h3>\n<p>For the sake of this tutorial I’m going to draw small waves using quick and choppy watercolor brush strokes. The technique is very similar to painting clouds using white, only in this case we’re using the same color we painted the water’s base with. The waves I’m painting are fairly flat so there’s no need to go overboard with the chop.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 24.363636363636363%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of watercolor wave chop technique\"\n        title=\"screenshot of watercolor wave chop technique\"\n        data-src=\"/static/e81fb0d4f8c07c4f5f860f745232d6fb/062c0/paper-53-wave-chop-dark.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/e81fb0d4f8c07c4f5f860f745232d6fb/16841/paper-53-wave-chop-dark.jpg 275w,\n/static/e81fb0d4f8c07c4f5f860f745232d6fb/50c97/paper-53-wave-chop-dark.jpg 550w,\n/static/e81fb0d4f8c07c4f5f860f745232d6fb/062c0/paper-53-wave-chop-dark.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<div class=\"custom-block notice\"><div class=\"custom-block-heading\">ProTip: use tints to lighten</div><div class=\"custom-block-body\"><p>If you go too dark, just mix white into your base coat color. Continue adding white until you get a color that has a hint of the base and lightens the water as you paint. It might take trial and error to find this “sweet spot.”</p></div></div>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 24.363636363636363%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"screenshot of watercolor wave chop lighten technique\" title=\"screenshot of watercolor wave chop lighten technique\" data-src=\"/static/934beca198818aae917058d182611f4f/062c0/paper-53-wave-chop-light.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/934beca198818aae917058d182611f4f/16841/paper-53-wave-chop-light.jpg 275w,\n/static/934beca198818aae917058d182611f4f/50c97/paper-53-wave-chop-light.jpg 550w,\n/static/934beca198818aae917058d182611f4f/062c0/paper-53-wave-chop-light.jpg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p>An example of lighter wave chops for those areas you may have painted too dark.</p></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<h3 id=\"under-painting-large-waves\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#under-painting-large-waves\" aria-label=\"under painting large waves permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Under painting large waves</h3>\n<p>Depending on the intensity of the waves this next step can be omitted. For larger waves with a lot of white foam, I like to paint a few more layers of blue anywhere these waves appear. The more layers, the darker the blue — the darker the blue, the higher the contrast there will be between the white wave foam we’ll be adding next…</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 58.909090909090914%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"wave photo reference photo\"\n        title=\"wave photo reference photo\"\n        data-src=\"/static/d63989cd4bf5893db5224b4b27881f31/062c0/paper-53-waves-photo.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/d63989cd4bf5893db5224b4b27881f31/16841/paper-53-waves-photo.jpg 275w,\n/static/d63989cd4bf5893db5224b4b27881f31/50c97/paper-53-waves-photo.jpg 550w,\n/static/d63989cd4bf5893db5224b4b27881f31/062c0/paper-53-waves-photo.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Using this photograph as reference, look for the large white areas of a wave and “underpaint<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup>” there.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1100px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 69.0909090909091%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of underpainted waves in dark blue\"\n        title=\"screenshot of underpainted waves in dark blue\"\n        data-src=\"/static/817ca8ca29d8bcffe39a8b08db4f579c/eacc7/paper-53-waves-underpainting-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/817ca8ca29d8bcffe39a8b08db4f579c/16841/paper-53-waves-underpainting-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/817ca8ca29d8bcffe39a8b08db4f579c/50c97/paper-53-waves-underpainting-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/817ca8ca29d8bcffe39a8b08db4f579c/eacc7/paper-53-waves-underpainting-lg.jpg 1100w,\n/static/817ca8ca29d8bcffe39a8b08db4f579c/cc4ba/paper-53-waves-underpainting-lg.jpg 1650w,\n/static/817ca8ca29d8bcffe39a8b08db4f579c/77bd5/paper-53-waves-underpainting-lg.jpg 2048w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<h2 id=\"waves-its-in-the-details\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#waves-its-in-the-details\" aria-label=\"waves its in the details permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Waves, it’s in the details</h2>\n<p>With a solid foundation set, it’s time to add the finishing spit and polish to our waves. Select the pencil tool and fill it with the same blue we used to base coat the water. It doesn’t have to be an exact match if you didn’t save the color in your palette, just something close is all that’s needed.</p>\n<p>Starting at the top of the water lightly sketch strokes from left to right. The severity of each wave will determine the direction and angle of these pencil lines — the larger the wave, the greater the angle.</p>\n<figure>\n  <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\" style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\">\n      <span class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\" style=\"padding-bottom: 43.27272727272728%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"></span>\n  <img class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\" alt=\"screenshot of wave lines using the base color\" title=\"screenshot of wave lines using the base color\" data-src=\"/static/b685762ba735ddf7f42610155c1b63c8/062c0/paper-53-wave-lines-blue.jpg\" data-srcset=\"/static/b685762ba735ddf7f42610155c1b63c8/16841/paper-53-wave-lines-blue.jpg 275w,\n/static/b685762ba735ddf7f42610155c1b63c8/50c97/paper-53-wave-lines-blue.jpg 550w,\n/static/b685762ba735ddf7f42610155c1b63c8/062c0/paper-53-wave-lines-blue.jpg 900w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\" loading=\"lazy\">\n    </span>\n  <figcaption><p>Use a blue-gray base color to draw in the smaller wave shapes.</p></figcaption>\n</figure>\n<p>A <a href=\"/mastering-paper/pogo-connect-smart-pen/\">Pogo Connect Smart Pen</a> works great for this step. It allows you to draw lightly and avoid going too heavy in an area. If you’re finger painting or using a normal capacitive stylus, remember to move quickly with your pencil strokes — the quicker you draw the lighter the mark.</p>\n<h3 id=\"white-wave-crests-and-foam\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#white-wave-crests-and-foam\" aria-label=\"white wave crests and foam permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>White wave crests and foam</h3>\n<p>Crests or areas where waves might be crashing against land I go heavy with a white pencil and try to make it textured and scratchy. Criss-crossing or hatching my strokes is one way of doing this quickly. If you remember my <a href=\"/mastering-paper/drawing-clouds/\">guide on painting clouds</a>, the technique is the same.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1100px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.36363636363636%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of wave foam zoomed in\"\n        title=\"screenshot of wave foam zoomed in\"\n        data-src=\"/static/f89706f2c0addd6b285839a8fd2c4a63/eacc7/paper-53-white-foam-detail-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/f89706f2c0addd6b285839a8fd2c4a63/16841/paper-53-white-foam-detail-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/f89706f2c0addd6b285839a8fd2c4a63/50c97/paper-53-white-foam-detail-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/f89706f2c0addd6b285839a8fd2c4a63/eacc7/paper-53-white-foam-detail-lg.jpg 1100w,\n/static/f89706f2c0addd6b285839a8fd2c4a63/cc4ba/paper-53-white-foam-detail-lg.jpg 1650w,\n/static/f89706f2c0addd6b285839a8fd2c4a63/77bd5/paper-53-white-foam-detail-lg.jpg 2048w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Draw wave crests and foam using a white pencil.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1100px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.36363636363636%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of finished wave foam\"\n        title=\"screenshot of finished wave foam\"\n        data-src=\"/static/1bb53d11f052ea7dc380220b1afe418d/eacc7/paper-53-white-foam-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/1bb53d11f052ea7dc380220b1afe418d/16841/paper-53-white-foam-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/1bb53d11f052ea7dc380220b1afe418d/50c97/paper-53-white-foam-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/1bb53d11f052ea7dc380220b1afe418d/eacc7/paper-53-white-foam-lg.jpg 1100w,\n/static/1bb53d11f052ea7dc380220b1afe418d/cc4ba/paper-53-white-foam-lg.jpg 1650w,\n/static/1bb53d11f052ea7dc380220b1afe418d/77bd5/paper-53-white-foam-lg.jpg 2048w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Depending on the size of the wave crests it’s usually easier to lightly paint in some highlights using a watercolor brush filled with white. Quickly dabbing or painting in short circular bursts will allow you to gradually lighten an area, without destroying the blue base coat beneath.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 48%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of crashing wave white areas using watercolor and white\"\n        title=\"screenshot of crashing wave white areas using watercolor and white\"\n        data-src=\"/static/c2851ef230b30ec8bd848c1c8bd864ce/062c0/paper-53-wave-foam-brush.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/c2851ef230b30ec8bd848c1c8bd864ce/16841/paper-53-wave-foam-brush.jpg 275w,\n/static/c2851ef230b30ec8bd848c1c8bd864ce/50c97/paper-53-wave-foam-brush.jpg 550w,\n/static/c2851ef230b30ec8bd848c1c8bd864ce/062c0/paper-53-wave-foam-brush.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Dabs of white can cover an area much faster than the pencil tool when filling in large shapes.</p>\n<h3 id=\"adding-shadows-to-the-waves\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#adding-shadows-to-the-waves\" aria-label=\"adding shadows to the waves permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Adding shadows to the waves</h3>\n<p>To add in shadows use a variation of the water’s base color, mixed with 20–40% black. Apply the same technique used above but with this darker color instead of white. Focus on putting a few pencil strokes of dark adjacent to the white strokes which will add depth to the waves. As always, if you over work an area just rewind or draw over it using white if it’s a shadow, and a shadow color if it’s white.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 900px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of wave shadow color mixture\"\n        title=\"screenshot of wave shadow color mixture\"\n        data-src=\"/static/457142bbb75636f3decb36bbcfd6fc23/062c0/paper-53-wave-shadow-mix.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/457142bbb75636f3decb36bbcfd6fc23/16841/paper-53-wave-shadow-mix.jpg 275w,\n/static/457142bbb75636f3decb36bbcfd6fc23/50c97/paper-53-wave-shadow-mix.jpg 550w,\n/static/457142bbb75636f3decb36bbcfd6fc23/062c0/paper-53-wave-shadow-mix.jpg 900w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>A pencil mixed with a dark blue-gray is perfect for refining edges and adding definition to smaller waves.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1100px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.36363636363636%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of wave shadows drawn in pencil\"\n        title=\"screenshot of wave shadows drawn in pencil\"\n        data-src=\"/static/9a44ce1a2b0c0fc811f9908131fd2e70/eacc7/paper-53-wave-shadows-zoom-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/9a44ce1a2b0c0fc811f9908131fd2e70/16841/paper-53-wave-shadows-zoom-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/9a44ce1a2b0c0fc811f9908131fd2e70/50c97/paper-53-wave-shadows-zoom-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/9a44ce1a2b0c0fc811f9908131fd2e70/eacc7/paper-53-wave-shadows-zoom-lg.jpg 1100w,\n/static/9a44ce1a2b0c0fc811f9908131fd2e70/cc4ba/paper-53-wave-shadows-zoom-lg.jpg 1650w,\n/static/9a44ce1a2b0c0fc811f9908131fd2e70/77bd5/paper-53-wave-shadows-zoom-lg.jpg 2048w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1100px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 68.36363636363636%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"screenshot of wave shadows drawn in pencil\"\n        title=\"screenshot of wave shadows drawn in pencil\"\n        data-src=\"/static/350614a8421112b6fa560a193f4ba571/eacc7/paper-53-wave-shadows-lg.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/350614a8421112b6fa560a193f4ba571/16841/paper-53-wave-shadows-lg.jpg 275w,\n/static/350614a8421112b6fa560a193f4ba571/50c97/paper-53-wave-shadows-lg.jpg 550w,\n/static/350614a8421112b6fa560a193f4ba571/eacc7/paper-53-wave-shadows-lg.jpg 1100w,\n/static/350614a8421112b6fa560a193f4ba571/cc4ba/paper-53-wave-shadows-lg.jpg 1650w,\n/static/350614a8421112b6fa560a193f4ba571/77bd5/paper-53-wave-shadows-lg.jpg 2048w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>Boom! And we’re done. Combined with a blue sky from my previous guide and you’ll have a landscape that looks like you drew it with traditional art supplies. Shhhhh…your secret is safe with me.</p>\n<h2 id=\"variations-on-a-theme\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#variations-on-a-theme\" aria-label=\"variations on a theme permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Variations on a theme</h2>\n<p>Using all of these techniques I was able to create a variety of backdrops for the portraits in my <a href=\"/paperfaces/\">PaperFaces Project</a>. Below are a few finished waterscapes to show what is possible by varying the color and composition.</p>\n<p><a href=\"/paperfaces/andrewbrewer-portrait/\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; background-color: var(--input-background-color); max-width: 1100px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 74.9090909090909%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image lazyload\"\n        alt=\"paperfaces andrewbrewer twitter\"\n        title=\"paperfaces andrewbrewer twitter\"\n        data-src=\"/static/497d5bc677a97264cc9c28eaa496dbda/eacc7/paperfaces-andrewbrewer-twitter.jpg\"\n        data-srcset=\"/static/497d5bc677a97264cc9c28eaa496dbda/16841/paperfaces-andrewbrewer-twitter.jpg 275w,\n/static/497d5bc677a97264cc9c28eaa496dbda/50c97/paperfaces-andrewbrewer-twitter.jpg 550w,\n/static/497d5bc677a97264cc9c28eaa496dbda/eacc7/paperfaces-andrewbrewer-twitter.jpg 1100w,\n/static/497d5bc677a97264cc9c28eaa496dbda/cc4ba/paperfaces-andrewbrewer-twitter.jpg 1650w,\n/static/497d5bc677a97264cc9c28eaa496dbda/77bd5/paperfaces-andrewbrewer-twitter.jpg 2048w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 1100px) 100vw, 1100px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"/paperfaces/sbrolins-portrait/\"><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right